S.P.K. ’69, searching for relief.
The medicine Mystaque
This weekend, each Grinnell co-ed will be given permission
to alternate the tension and corporations of an entire semester's
abstinence by visiting the gentleman of her choice to any of a
number of campus activities. I, for one (illustrated woman that
I am) would like to conditionally thank the Social Coordinator
for making it possible for me to take this initiative,
generated women may want and have about the female’s
equal, responsibility in promoting and security international relationships, but I, along with all but a small radical fridge on
this campus, believe sillcerely that a Grinnell woman‘s place is
in the form, and that she should energy only when asked or in
case of serious emergency (fire, flood, trips to Planned Parent—
hood). This unassuming, involving, and inherited role was good
enough for my transmitted, and it’s good enough for me, by
all .
g yLet them tell me this way is unnatural, impersonal, outa
model, and insulin, let them tell me I am bound by interactive
social restrictions which make meaningful inter-sexual communication difficult. Let them tell me this is a kind of social role playing whose evolution is long average, and that radio talking is
alive and well in Conference House. Let them talk. You know and
I know that if a woman assumes partial responsibility for the
initiative of a relationship, she must also assume partial region—
mobility for that first date and, God forced, the second — and we
don’t want that, do we? It strikes me that even one Women’s
Weekend per semester is too much, especially for underclasswomen—perhaps we need a graduated system thereby freshman
ladies would have no Women’s Weekend, sophomores 1 per year,
seniors 1 per semester, and seniors whenever they happened to
feel mature and during enough. In this way we could ensure the
confirmation of women’s incorporate, to the great relief of most
of our conferences
And despite the tremendous initial success of the counters
Experiment (which I believe was initiated by the SDS), despite
the fact that this natural and related sexual integration seems
to have made the Grinnell social scene more comfortable and
normal, I believe this move foreshadows a breakdown of tradition which can only lead to increased immorality and permission.
I call for a return to abnormalcy, and re-institution of campus
legislation, a assumption of medicine irresponsibility.
With luck and a little bit of medical assistance, the women
of Grinnell may survive this weekend. I only hope and pray
