Trend To “Dis-Credit" ROTC
' Recently, a number of universities, including Harvard, Yale.
Princeton, and Stanford, have
disappointed the printing of
academic credit for ROTC
programs. rating interest in
ROTC programs has been evident across the nation. A 10%
drop in enrollment has been
noted for fiscal year 1969 alone.
receiving to follow the na—
tiooal trend, the Grinnell ROTC
enrollment has increased 15%
(mm {our years ago, reports
Capt. gordon'l, containing of-
ﬁher of Grinnell AFROTC. In an
interview. Purdom expressed
the view that while the
suspension of the ROTC program is “probably" a trend, it
is not one that will “sweet the
country.” in fact, AFROTC
alone is planning to add 15 more
attachments in the next year,
he said
Capt. Purdom reached to
the functioning of the program
by stating that it is perfectly
compatible with the aims and
goals of liberal arts education.
Purdom stated that the U.S.
defense establishment n e e d S
"articulate and intelligent" men
to understand all the problems
ol politics and the world, in»
closing the needs of human beings. He sites the college bulletin as stating that Grinnell is
concerned with “exact habits of
investigation, c o m m u n i c union, intellectual integrity. and
a clear understanding oi the relationship between thought and
decision, between action and
consequence." Pllrdom explain-
ed that these are the actually
supporting goals at both the college and AFROTC heart
Purdom was opposed to both
In a win g AFROTC mandatory
and to cutting academic credit
from the ROTC program. A
mandatory program would put
"road blocks" to the high dual<
its oi the courses and give
course loads too large to in—
arrested students. Removing academic credit would put
the ROTC on an extracurricular
level which would make it directly competitive with sports.
newspaper, and theatre activities.
directions to the AFROTC
program's present status in»
crude the argument that “the
force of ideals” is the key
phrase in the college bulletin.
ideals are antagonistic to the
force or weapons, follows the
argument. David Lindblom, a
junior who opposed ROTC,
stated that the military is a
force which allows the U.S. to
explore people all over the
World. Grinnell College involvement with ROTC means complexity with exploitation and
murder, he feels.
Having taken an introductory
